r indigenous scholars, and elaborates on its poetic quality. Luiseño artist James Luna considers Tac's contemporary significance in a series of artworks that bring Pablo Tac into provocative juxtaposition with the present day.Transcribed by Marta Eguía, Cecilia Palmeiro, Laura León Llerena, Jussara Quadros, and Heidi Morse, with facing-page translation by Jaime Cortez, Guillermo Delgado, Gildas Hamel, Karl Kottman, Heidi Morse, and Rose Vekony  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aIndian scholarsxBiographyxCalifornia. 0aIndian scholarszCaliforniavBiography. 0aLuiseño IndiansxBiographyxCalifornia. 0aLuiseño IndiansxHistory. 0aLuiseño IndianszCaliforniavBiography. 0aLuiseño languagevDictionaries. 0aLuiseño languagexDictionaries. 0aLuiseño languagexGrammar. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aHaas, Lisbeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520950290423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520950290.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles